'''Parascience''' is the study of subjects that are outside the scope of the [[Natural science|natural]] and [[social science]]s because they cannot be explained by accepted [[scientific theory]] or tested by conventional [[scientific method]]s.<ref>Collins English Dictionary. Copyright Harper Collins Publishers</ref> This study may be concerned with [[phenomena]] assumed to be beyond the scope of [[scientific inquiry]] or for which no scientific explanation exists. The parasciences include [[history]], [[philosophy]], [[art]], and [[religion]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book | url = https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/sum2017/entries/pseudo-science/ | title = The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy | last = Hansson | first = Sven Ove | date = 2017 | publisher = Metaphysics Research Lab, Stanford University | editor-last = Zalta | editor-first = Edward N. | edition = Summer 2017 }}</ref>
Parascience can also be defined as a subject, method, etc., purporting to be scientific but regarded as unorthodox or unacceptable by the [[scientific community]]; an "alternative" science.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018|reason=This sounds like a definition for pseudoscience}}
